1 (e) Communication with assistive technology devices.
2 2. “Dyslexia” means a neurological learning disability
3 characterized by difficulties with accurate and fluent word
4 recognition and poor spelling and decoding abilities that typically
5 result from a deficit in the phonological component of language.
6 3. “Dyslexia intervention” means systematic, multisensory
7 intervention offered in an appropriate setting that is derived from
8 evidence-based research.
9 4. “Individualized education program” has the meaning
10 ascribed to it in 20 U.S.C. § 1414(d)(1)(A).
11 5. “Individualized education program team” has the meaning
12 ascribed to it in 20 U.S.C. § 1414(d)(1)(B).
13 6. “Provider of special education” means a school within a
14 school district or charter school that provides education or services
15 to pupils with disabilities or any other entity that is responsible for
16 providing education or services to a pupil with a disability for a
17 school district or charter school.
18 7. “Pupil who receives early intervening services” means a
19 person enrolled in kindergarten or grades 1 to 12, inclusive, who is
20 not a pupil with a disability but who needs additional academic and
21 behavioral support to succeed in a regular school program.
22 8. “Pupil with a disability” means a “child with a disability,” as
23 that term is defined in 20 U.S.C. § 1401(3)(A), who is under 22
24 years of age.
25 9. “Response to scientific, research-based intervention” means
26 a collaborative process which assesses a pupil’s response to
27 scientific, research-based intervention that is matched to the needs
28 of a pupil and that systematically monitors the level of performance
29 and rate of learning of the pupil over time for the purpose of making
30 data-based decisions concerning the need of the pupil for
31 increasingly intensified services.
32 10. “Specific learning disability” means a disorder in one or
33 more of the basic psychological processes involved in understanding
34 or using spoken or written language which is not primarily the result
35 of a visual, hearing or motor impairment, intellectual disability,
36 serious emotional disturbance, or an environmental, cultural or
37 economic disadvantage. Such a disorder may manifest itself in an
38 imperfect ability to listen, think, speak, read, write, spell or perform
39 mathematical calculations. The term includes, without limitation,
40 perceptual disabilities, brain injury, minimal brain dysfunction,
41 dyslexia and developmental aphasia.
42 Sec. 3. The provisions of NRS 354.599 do not apply to any
